@@ -0,0 +1,134 @@
+# name: test/sql/join/positional/test_positional_join.test
+# description: Test positional joins
+# group: [positional]
+
+statement ok
+PRAGMA enable_verification
+
+statement ok
+CREATE TABLE two (a INTEGER, b INTEGER);
+
+statement ok
+INSERT INTO two VALUES (11, 1), (12, 2);
+
+statement ok
+CREATE TABLE three AS 
+	SELECT * FROM (VALUES
+		(11, 1),
+		(12, 2),
+		(13, 3)
+	) tbl(a, b);
+
+statement ok
+CREATE TABLE threek AS
+	SELECT * FROM generate_series(0, 3001) tbl(id);
+
+#
+# Positional Scan
+#
+
+# Basic test
+query IIII
+SELECT * 
+FROM two t1 POSITIONAL JOIN two t2 
+----
+11	1	11	1
+12	2	12	2
+
+# Multiple blocks
+query II
+SELECT *
+FROM threek t1 POSITIONAL JOIN threek t2
+WHERE t1.id <> t2.id
+----
+
+# Outer semantics
+query IIII
+SELECT * 
+FROM two t1 POSITIONAL JOIN three t2 
+----
+11	1	11	1
+12	2	12	2
+NULL	NULL	13	3
+
+query IIII
+SELECT * 
+FROM three t1 POSITIONAL JOIN two t2 
+----
+11	1	11	1
+12	2	12	2
+13	3	NULL	NULL
+
+query II
+SELECT COUNT(a), COUNT(id)
+FROM three POSITIONAL JOIN threek
+----
+3	3002
+
+query II
+SELECT COUNT(id), COUNT(a)
+FROM threek POSITIONAL JOIN three
+----
+3002	3
+
+#
+# Positional Join
+#
+
+# Basic test
+query IIII
+SELECT *
+FROM 
+	(SELECT * FROM two WHERE a % 2 = 0) t1
+	POSITIONAL JOIN
+	(SELECT * FROM two WHERE a % 2 = 1) t2
+----
+12	2	11	1
+
+# Multiple blocks
+query II
+SELECT *
+FROM 
+	(SELECT * FROM threek WHERE id % 2 = 0) t1
+	POSITIONAL JOIN
+	(SELECT * FROM threek WHERE id % 2 = 1) t2
+WHERE t1.id + 1 <> t2.id
+
+# Outer semantics
+query IIII
+SELECT *
+FROM 
+	(SELECT * FROM three WHERE a % 2 = 1) t1
+	POSITIONAL JOIN
+	(SELECT * FROM two WHERE a % 2 = 0) t2
+----
+11	1	12	2	
+13	3	NULL	NULL
+
+query IIII
+SELECT *
+FROM 
+	(SELECT * FROM two WHERE a % 2 = 0) t1
+	POSITIONAL JOIN
+	(SELECT * FROM three WHERE a % 2 = 1) t2
+----
+12	2	11	1
+NULL	NULL	13	3
+
+query II
+SELECT COUNT(t1.id), COUNT(t2.id)
+FROM 
+	(SELECT * FROM threek WHERE id % 2 = 0) t1
+	POSITIONAL JOIN
+	(SELECT * FROM threek WHERE id % 3 = 0) t2
+----
+1501	1001
+
+query II
+SELECT COUNT(t1.id), COUNT(t2.id)
+FROM 
+	(SELECT * FROM threek WHERE id % 3 = 0) t2
+	POSITIONAL JOIN
+	(SELECT * FROM threek WHERE id % 2 = 0) t1
+----
+1501	1001

problem_statement:
Efficient row by row join equivalent of pd.concat axis=1
I'm looking for a fast way to simply combine the columns of multiple tables/parquet files/pandas dataframes and I'm not sure I'm not overlooking something in duckdb.

Here's an example:
We simply have two tables `df1` and `df2` that we would like to write into a single table (the row indices don't matter, we guarantee that they have the same number of rows).

```python
import duckdb
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
n, m = 10_000, 100
df1=pd.DataFrame(np.random.random((n, m)), columns=[f"df1_{i}" for i in range(m)]).reset_index()
df2=pd.DataFrame(np.random.random((n, m)), columns=[f"df2_{i}" for i in range(m)]).reset_index()
ddb = duckdb.connect()
```

Using python and pandas:

```python
In [42]: %timeit pd.concat([df1, df2], axis=1, join="inner")
28.7 ms ± 495 µs per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 10 loops each)
```

Using duckdb the way I came up with is a simple join:

```python
In [43]: %timeit ddb.execute("select * from df1 inner join df2 on df1.index=df2.index")
40.9 ms ± 1.54 ms per loop (mean ± std. dev. of 7 runs, 10 loops each)
```

I'm assuming this is slower because we're potentially allowing for a lot more complex cases to be handled in the joining:
```
┌───────────────────────────┐                             
│         HASH_JOIN         │                             
│   ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─   │                             
│            LEFT           ├──────────────┐              
│        index=index        │              │              
└─────────────┬─────────────┘              │                                           
┌─────────────┴─────────────┐┌─────────────┴─────────────┐
│        PANDAS_SCAN        ││        PANDAS_SCAN        │
│   ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─   ││   ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─ ─   │
│           index           ││           index           │
│           df1_0           ││           df2_0           │
│           df1_1           ││           df2_1           │
```

Is there any way to simply combine the columns efficiently completely ignoring any sort of joins or column values?
Or is this basically the correct way to do this sort of simple combining of tables?
hints_text:
I think DuckDB does not have a positional join implementation yet - I agree that this would be a desirable new feature!

PS: you can now work around this omission by creating an index on `index`, but, the indices are not yet persistent, so this is only a viable alternative if the query performance improvement outweighs the creation of the index, or you issue many different queries that each need this join on index.
This sounds like an outer join on rowid? If so, we should look at making that fast.
This is the feature I miss the most for columnar databases. As a programmer, I am not aware of any language complaining about writting:
for(int i=0; i<n;i++) do_something_with(a[i], b[i]);
How a, b were generated, sorted, resized is nobody concern. Associating two result columns coming from different computations should be allowed. Positional join, as a language extension should be a cheap way of associating data resulting from diferrent computations. 

select a.x, a.y, b.z from a positional join b over (ordered by a.rowid, b.rowid !! is not the same as regular join) would be ideal. In case a and b records count differ, the join should fail. The missing over () contents should instruct the engine to use current processing order to align the resulting values. 

Or at least teach me how to do on tables: 
update a.field = b.field from a, b; 
with no explicit match, just natural/storage order.


@danz68 Yeah positional join is a common column store physical operator, and the last one I built had it. We are just discussing how to make it parallel so it is faster!
@danz68 I started to have a look at this and I have to say that the performance is only about ⅓ slower (40ms vs 30ms), which is hardly surprising since we are copying 200 columns into `DataChunk`s and back. I'm not convinced this warrants a separate physical  join operator, but it might if the tables were longer (e.g., 10MR instead of 10KR). I will check the performance at scale some more, but I suspect that this is only worth doing if the hash table gets large.

In any case, I think the way to express most of the operations you are asking about is to join on `rowid`. This is just the syntax SQL uses to express these kinds of operations. It isn't really any different from the `i` index in the procedural example you gave. The loop example would be:

```sql
SELECT do_something(a.*, b.*)
FROM a, b
WHERE a.rowid = b.rowid
```
and the update example would be:

```sql
UPDATE a.field = b.field
FROM a, b
WHERE a.rowid = b.rowid
```

I'm not clear what you meant by:

> select a.x, a.y, b.z from a positional join b over (ordered by a.rowid, b.rowid !! is not the same as regular join) would be ideal. In case a and b records count differ, the join should fail. The missing over () contents should instruct the engine to use current processing order to align the resulting values.

SQL would express this as a join, again on `rowid`, no `OVER` clause required. If you want to detect missing values, you can use an outer join that will insert `NULL`s into the join result - including `rowid` so you could distinguish missing matches from input  `NULL`s.

I think the fundamental conceptual issue here is that SQL operates on _sets_ but Python operates on _arrays_. The set model allows us to do fun things like independent parallel processing of data and out-of-memory processing, but it also means that you have to be explicit about ordering semantics. This may be syntactically onerous at times, but it is just a trade-off necessitated by a different way of thinking about data.  Still, if you can clarify the request a bit I'll think about it some more.

(I can see using `POSITIONAL JOIN` as syntactic sugar for `rowid = rowid` - that would fit in with our "friendly SQL" mantra. Is that what you meant?)
Right now you have implemented loop, merge and hash joins. Each of them with its own use case. A positional join, would be just a syntactic sugar for t1.crt_posid=t2.crt_posid (not the same with rowid, which depends on order and possible deleted records).

Internally would be
for (i=0;i<n;i++) get t1.a[i], t2.b[i]. 
(no specific joining condition, just use the aligned position of current t1 and t2 order)
What is the difference between `rowid` and `crt_posid`?
_"In the current storage, these identifiers are contiguous unsigned integers (0, 1, …) if no rows were deleted. Deletions introduce gaps in the rowids which may be reclaimed later. Therefore, it is strongly recommended not to use rowids as identifiers."_

if rowid is storage related, 
select rowid, f from t 
returns the storage order
0, "B"
1, "A"

select rowid, f from t order by f
(probably) returns
1, "A"
0, "B"

select crt_posid(), f from t
should return
0, "B"
1, "A"

select crt_posid(), f from t order by f
should return
0, "A"
1, "B"

I don't need any form of internal join, a simplified rowid storage join would look like
for (i=0;i<t1.n;i++) {
  a_t1 = t1.a[i];
  ri = t1.rowid[i];
  if ( t2.findbyrowid(ri, &j) ) 
    a_t2 = t2.a[j]; 
  else 
    a_t2 = nul;
}

from my perspective, a positional join would look like
for (i=0;i<t1.n;i++) {
 a_t1 = t1.a[i];
 a_t2 = i<t2.n ? t2.a[i]: nil;
}

which, of course, can be also written as

if (t1.n<=t2.n)
 for (i=0;i<t1.n;i++) {
 a_t1 = t1.a[i];
 a_t2 = t2.a[i];
}
else
{
for (i=0;i<t2.n;i++) {
 a_t1 = t1.a[i];
 a_t2 = t2.a[i];
}
for (i=t2.n;i<t1.n;i++) {
 a_t1 = t1.a[i];
 a_t2 = nil;
}
}






A `positional join` physical operator would be a very valuable addition.

In a preliminary exploration with the JSON extension, I have worked around the lack of such a join by enforcing an index on `rowid`, such that at least an index join is selected. Yet, this is impractical for at least three reasons: the index join would be more expensive than the positional equivalent, we do not really need the index, and, for now, the indexes are not persistent so have to be recreated every time you start your program.
Thanks for all the clarifications and feedback!  I am working on a first cut at this with @Mytherin for physical tables. 

One proposal for `ORDER BY` is to reuse the `rowid` pseudo-column for subqueries e.g.,

```sql
select rowid, f from t order by f
```
would return

| rowid | f |
|--:|:--|
| 1 | A |
| 0 | B |

but

```sql
select s.rowid, f from (select f from t order by f) s
```

would return:

| s.rowid | f |
| --:| :-- |
| 0 | A |
| 1 | B |

Then physical join orders could be mixed between tables and ordered subqueries. It could also allow for outer and inner join semantics.

A second proposal would be to add `POSITIONAL JOIN` as a join qualifier (like `INNER JOIN`). This has the advantage of making everything explicit and avoiding things like pseudo-columns and missing match tests, at the cost of adding non-standard syntax. We may be able to get the best of both worlds by optimising `rowid` joins with appropriate conditions into PJ internally, so this may not be much of an issue.
This is "raw and wriggling", but the perf improvement on the benchmark is about 15x.
Ideally, if t1.f is identical with t2.f,
select a,b,c,..,f from t1;
should be as fast as
select t1.a, t1.b, t1.c, ... , **t2.f** from t1 positional join t2 on t1.rowid=t2.rowid;


> Ideally, if t1.f is identical with t2.f,
> select a,b,c,..,f from t1;
> should be as fast as
> select t1.a, t1.b, t1.c, ... , **t2.f** from t1 positional join t2 on t1.rowid=t2.rowid;

Easy enough to benchmark.

We are closing in on a spec.  Explicit use of `POSITIONAL JOIN` will have the requested semantics and throw if there is a row count mismatch. It will work with `ORDER BY` subqueries as well. 

We will also have the keyhole optimisation I have been testing for the cases where we can determine it applies (ordered, dense, unique keys with a shared base). This includes the basic `rowid` and any other join keys we can determine this for. This optimisation will also support outer join semantics for mismatched table sizes.
The keyhole version would come first as it doesn't require changes to the optimiser, but hopefully it will make life better.
About to take another pass at this, so I'm going to throw in some notes.
